Marc,<br><br>
I feel there has to be an acknowledgement that there is &quot;the good, the bad, and the ugly&quot;, even on this site. Though the good here far outweighs anything that has ever been said in the heat of the moment, the Vietnam War has a divided legacy that is important for people to see.<br><br>
From a Vietnam Veteran's perspective, there are many 'Nam Vets who still feel the sting, the hurt, the pain, of the demonstrable rejection they received upon their return from combat. The average combat arms Vietnam Veteran was dumped into the civilian sector within days of killing the enemy to survive, only to discover that there was &quot;an enemy within&quot;. Home was no longer the traditional safe place of refuge.<br><br>
Weak minded people viciously turned upon the returning Vietnam Veteran for no good reason. We see discrimination, hatred, and derision, to this day. Many Vietnam Veterans carry the scars of these altercations and will consequently react very predictably and strongly when confronted with such behavior to this day. <br><br>
Who wouldn't?<br><br>
If there are those who wish to play with some Vietnam Veterans with these triggers, then the reception they receive should not be unexpected or surprising.<br><br>
The lingering &quot;firefight&quot; is an important legacy that must be acknowledged, regardless of the words that have been spoken. This society must see the fruit of its past decisions. Perhaps these mistakes of the Vietnam War will not be repeated with those who now patriotically bear arms for all of us. 
